[start section id="20103"]

1. January 2006, rectal cancer, adenocarcinoma 12-cm from the anal verge, a low-anterior resection performed for a T2, N0 disease, observed.
2. April 30, 2010, adenocarcinoma 12-cm from the anal verge, at the anastomosis, and the rectal ultrasound showed this to be T3, N1.  CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis showed left posterior lateral presacral adenopathy as well as perirectal lymph nodes.  Treated with 5-FU by continuous infusion concurrently with radiation therapy.
I had the pleasure to meet Mrs. Work, a delightful 65-year-old woman from the suburbs of Pine Bluff, otherwise very healthy.  The history is as above.  She received 5-FU with continuous infusion concurrently with radiation therapy.  Also 5-FU was initially decreased by 25% due to mucositis.  Later, she developed anterior neck pain and anterior and superior chest pain with the dose of 5-FU decreased by another 25%.  She did not have a pulmonary embolism as per CT angiogram, and a cardiac evaluation including stress test came back negative.  The pain slowly improved over days with the use of Vicodin, and it disappeared even while receiving 5-FU.  She received her last dose of chemotherapy and radiation therapy on July 6, 2010.  She is up and about and asymptomatic.

[end section id="20103"]

